  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "Evolution has converged to a local optimum where all three fitness components (survival, beauty, efficiency) reward the same morphology: organisms that are individually optimized for resource acquisition. Breaking plateau requires *decoupling* these components so they reward *different* body plans — make it profitable to be beautiful even if it costs survival, make cooperation valuable even if individual efficiency drops. The plateau exists because the fitness landscape has a single peak; you need to add new dimensions that create multiple peaks.; [hard] Introduce phenotypic modularity: enable organisms to grow heterogeneous body segments with independent cell type specialization (sensory clusters, energy stores, structural supports, signaling nodes). Segments can develop independently during growth, creating combinatorial body plan diversity. — Current plateau suggests all organisms are converging to single optimal morphology. Modular growth creates 10x more body-plan combinations without changing physics. Evolution can explore radically different solutions: long-thin foragers vs compact clusters vs distributed collectives. This breaks the constraint that all bodies must be similar.; [easy] Add temporal beauty dimension: organisms gain fitness for periodic behaviors (synchronized pulsing, rhythmic color patterns, coordinated group motion). Implement circadian-like cycles where phenotype score includes phase coherence and pattern regularity at multiple timescales. — Current beauty metrics are likely static (shape, color, symmetry at snapshot). Adding temporal dimension rewards novelty: organisms can become beautiful through *behavior*, not just form. This opens entirely new selection pressure orthogonal to survival, decoupling beauty from immediate reproductive advantage and breaking the survival-dominated plateau.; [medium] Enable energy pooling via proximity: organisms within close range can form temporary metabolic networks, sharing energy at a cost. This creates selection pressure for clustering and cooperative colonies without changing individual organism genetics or reproduction rules. — Current fitness likely rewards individual-level optimization (eat, grow, survive). Pooling adds group-level fitness function. Suddenly sparse-cooperative morphologies become viable. Evolution can discover swarm/colonial strategies that were impossible when every organism competed as individuals. Structural change to fitness calculation, not just parameters.",
